< Review>
The finest prime rib, tri tip and ribs.  The ribs and prime rib are so exquisite you will never taste anything as good ever again.

I recommend everything on this menu.  If you can go out, there is truly nowhere else you want to go.

I also MUST mention that these people know how to cook meat.  They cook the prime rib and steaks and even tri tip to a point of rareness that is proper medium rare and yet somehow not bloody at all.

Yes, rare but not bloody at all.  That is perfection.</Review>

< Review>
Great local bar & restaurant! Service is outstanding. Drinks poured with a slightly heavy hand - which works for me! Not overwhelming, just feeling like you get your $$ worth. Love the tri tip and mac-n-cheese. Hubby gets pasta and clam chowder. Denny is almost always there and takes the time to get to know us personally. Just love the warmth! Infinitely better than typical big city annominity. Decor could be refreshed but the food and family feel supercede the aging finishes. Come to the strand and enjoy old-time family closeness, great food & drinks! Remember to say hi to Denny and his wife, Karen!< /Review>

<Text>For at least the last 12 years, I've had issues with my neck and back.  Sometimes the symptoms would get pretty scary.  I've had numbness in my hands and feet; I've had constant fatigue in my arms; I've had my feet fall asleep while running; I've even woken up in the middle of the night with absolutely no feeling in my arms or legs.  I've been to numerous doctors, and they've always told me the same thing: It's a nerve issue-there's nothing seriously wrong with you.

I lived with those symptoms for years.  It just became a part of my life.  Then I visited with Dr. Cecilia.

I told her my story.  She was not satisfied with my "just live with it" approach.  She wanted me to see her immediately.

On my first visit, Dr. Cecilia set me up for XRays.  At her office, she has this AWESOME 3-D X-ray machine.  I can't even explain it, you just have to go see it.

When Dr. Cecilia saw the results, she was a little horrified.  She saw the consequences of multiple sports/snowboarding related injuries, and told me my body had been slowly contorting to accommodate for a twisted spine.  She showed me exactly where my nerves were being pinched and could correspond those nerves to the symptoms I was experiencing.  She taught me more about my neck and back in 15 minutes than dozens of doctors had in my entire life.

Dr. Cecilia set me up with a plan.  The initial visit obviously involved an adjustment.  After ONE ADJUSTMENT, I started feeling better. ONE.  All that pressure on my brain stem; released.  I've been seeing her for about 3 weeks, and my adjustment has held.  I haven't felt this good since I was in high school. I'm sleeping 8-9 hours a night uninterrupted, my digestion is better, I have more energy, I just feel better.

After 12 years of thinking I was going to live with these symptoms for the rest of my life, she's fixing me. I sought a chiropractor for my pain and had been going to him for 2 years, but I never got any lasting results, not even with massage therapy.

My discomfort was causing me a lot of stress and frustration. It would interfere with my work as I have to drive long distances on a weekly basis and lift heavy objects. My knees would start hurting after long periods of standing and in the last two years I started to notice that I was developing a weak grip in my right hand.  When I met Dr. Jessica, she asked about my digestion and I told her that I have had acid reflux for my whole life and I would have to take medication to relieve my symptoms. Often, I would be up in the middle of the night feeling the reflux, which prevented me from getting any rest. I did not realize at the time that chiropractic had anything to do with my digestion.

After a few gentle adjustments, I have noticed significant changes in how my body functions. My low back no longer bothers me, even when I drive long distance. My body feels better and more balanced, and the most surprising thing is that my acid reflux has cleared up! I no longer have to take medication to manage the reflux and I can sleep through the night. Even my family members have noticed that I no longer have to take pills.

I have more energy during the day, my thoughts are much clearer (no more brain fog), and my body feels much more balanced. I feel great!<//review>

< Review>
I was experiencing a painful week right arm stemming from an impingement  of C4 or C5 in my neck.  I could barely lift the arm it was numb and extremely week.
Kaisers approach was to operate which I was opposed to.  So a friend of mine who is a Chiropractor recommended I look for an upper cervical spine chiropractor using the Blair Technique.
So on the internet is how I found Dr. Lee.  Skeptical at firs YES.  I had the X Rays done and went to one of her new patient classes then started treatment I was desperate for results.
Dr. Lee is very well spoken and explained her process to the finest detail which is great because this process is not like any Chiropractic I had had before, no Cracking or Popping just mellow light adjustments after a thorough evaluation on each visit.  So No Popping or Cracking, I thought how can this work (look up the Blair Technique and the science behind it).

There has even been plenty of visits where I did not need an adjustment because the previous one was holding, which is the end goal of chiropractic.

After about a month on  my individual plan which included visits and home excessive I started to have better control and strength in my Right arm.  Each month even more.  Now at about six months out (I think)  I am completely back to Rock climbing, Surfing, Playing basketball and all the other things I do no more neck pain or arm weakness.  I am still in the stage of my plan where I see Dr. Lee about once a week and am regularly holding adjustments for 2-3 weeks at a time sometimes more.  I am consistently trying things that I wasn't able to do 6 moths earlier that I had done before my neck started causing pain.

I have never been excited to see that I have a Dr. Appointment coming up until now,  when I know that I beet my body up over the weekend, Dr. Lee puts me straight again.

I highly Recommend researching Upper Cervical Spine Care and the technique that Dr. Lee practices, Go visit her and get back on the path to enjoying a health life.

I was totally skeptical and I let Dr. Lee know that but now I am a firm believer in upper cervical spine care.

If your starting to have pain or had it for a long time and traditional Chiropractic either scares you or docent work, it's Time to check out Upper Cervical Chiropractic and of course Dr. Lee.

I waited this long to post (which I never review anything) to make sure I could make an honest recommendation.

Thanks for reading and good luck and good research

Thank you Dr. Lee for putting me back together (today).

Mike S

< Text>
About 2 weeks ago, I drove nearly an hour in traffic all the way there and back because of the impressive reviews I read.

My best friend in the entire world has been battling some type of infection for a couple of years now and no one can seem to tell me what is happening because the tests they make me choose between are not producing results. So while my bank account is depleting, theirs is growing.

Which leads me to my reasoning for the 1 star review.

After explaining my cat's symptoms, I was presented with a choice between 3 tests. Um, what?

I am not a veterinarian nor am I a professional in diagnosing issues with animals. Why should I have to choose between 3 different tests hoping that I pick the right one? I'm basically having to gamble with my money and pets health? No thank you!

Of course, the doctor called me and told me the test I chose came back with no results. What a surprise...
I asked her why she could not have recommended 1 test to me that would have been the best to start with based off of the symptoms I explained. To which she replied "Well we had a cat before who..."
I don't care about what your cat went through. I care about my cat!

These tests are not cheap, the office visit is not cheap, and neither is medication.
When I go to the doctor and explain my symptoms, I'm presented with the best place to start and if that doesn't work then we go on to option #2 and etc. Why can't they do the same for pets?

Look at my poor baby! That photo is her current condition. This is everything that I explained to the doctor that was happening! It gets worse as the days go by.

On top of that, I gathered all of her vet records that I could get a hold of and they told ME to go through it and find what medications she had been previously prescribed so when they figure out what's wrong with her they will know what to give her.
That is not my job. That's what I'm paying you for!
I work a very busy schedule and the only free time I have is on weekends and most vets are not open on Sundays.

Very disappointed with the entire experience. I feel taken advantage of and unless they can make it right, I will not be returning.</Text>

< Review>
I rarely write reviews but very much feel like I need to in this case.

To sum it up: Had a tooth that I viewed was cracked, it was a tad sensitive to pressure but there was no pain. I called my regular dentist and couldn't get a soon enough appointment, so I called this place. Thankfully they could accommodate me and take my health insurance.  So they do the x-ray everything to this point is going fine. But once the x-rays are over they tell me I have periodontal disease (gum disease) and need to start  treatment right away pointing to the sign on the wall advertising periodontal treatment. This came as a surprise considering I came in for a cracked tooth. Like any regular person trusting who I view as medical professionals I agree to treatment but want to know the cost and details (what does it entail, etc). They bring me a $1,500 bill saying my insurance doesn't cover it. Obviously this was a bill I couldn't afford and they did offer a payment plan (that I still couldn't afford).

But something in my gut was saying "This doesn't make sense or sound right" so I said I'd think about it. Then they present me with a form to initial saying that by not taking their recommendation for the periodontal treatment I am risking tooth and bone loss. That was scary to be frank. Then I said "Hey what about my tooth?" which again was the whole reason I came in. The dentist casually says "Oh you need a crown" and asks the dental assistant  to find out if insurance will cover it. They then present me with another bill also around the $1,500 for this crown. This also hit me wrong because I felt like they overlooked the very thing I mentioned, pointed out and came in to check. I left not choosing any of their treatment and felt like something was just not right.

I called my regular dentist again and asked them to pencil me in if someone cancels, I'll take any appointment. Thankfully someone did cancel which meant I got seen soon after by my regular dentist. After x-rays and a very through exam my dentist said that I do not have gum disease and I do not need a crown. It wasn't my actual tooth cracking/coming out but it was an old filling. So basically I need a filling repaired and a tooth next to it gets a filling as well.

While I can say the place seemed clean and the people were nice...the way they are practicing business here is shady. If a dentist here tells you something... get a second opinion. In retrospect it feels like they were just trying to get money out of me and I think they tried to scare me in order to do it. I truly hope they clean up their act.< /Review>

< Text>
I had a horrible experience at this dentist office. I went in for a new patient exam because I had moved out of state, and was hoping for a teeth cleaning with the hygienist after. I have always had a good experience with dentists in the past and go every six months for check-ups with regular teeth cleanings, never had a cavity and one dentist told me to go eat a brownie. When this dentist greeted me, she did not introduce herself, and the first thing she said to me was, "have you ever had a deep cleaning?" I said I didn't think so and she proceeded to do the gum readings. She was very rough so I began to wince, and she told me to hold still and that I was making it worse by flinching. There were a few 4s in the back but no 5s. After this, she told me some of my gums were bleeding and I had bone loss and that I needed a deep cleaning. The assistant printed off the treatment option which totaled $1354. I was surprised, so I asked her why this was necessary and she just repeated what she said earlier about my gums bleeding. They also asked if I had a Care Credit Card and had I not said that I already had one, they probably would have had me apply for one! It should be noted that Care Credit is a high interest card that can be useful if you qualify for a no-interest promotional period and can pay it off in 6 months or so. It is the type of credit arrangement that can get you into debt if you're not careful, but providers like Western Dental like it because they get their money upfront.

On top of that, the dentist came back in and asked me to give a review of her assistant WHILE I WAS STILL SITTING IN THE CHAIR! She asked me if I had a phone, got it out of my purse, took it out of my hand and showed me the review app. I clicked 3 stars because I thought I was rating the nice-ness of the assistant and the doctor then said no, no I needed to give 5 stars so her assistant could get a free lunch. After I walked out of the office I came to my senses and walked back in to say I had changed my mind about the Perio Tray. <Gmap_id>0x80857e9e78ab5d65:0x7a731e7ebbeb697f<//Gmap_id>< Text>
When I cracked a tooth while on vacation, I went to Western Dental because it was the only place around that had an open appointment at short notice.

They listened carefully while I explained I was on vacation and couldn't come back for a second treatment, and then proceeded to write up a treatment plant that needed me to come back for another visit.  I got charged for this plan (full ceramic onlay).

In conversation with the dentist, she finally understood that I was leaving California in a couple days, so she changed my treatment plant (to a simple crown, which my home dentist said was really all I needed) and said I'd get a refund.

That was seventeen months ago.  I've call probably a dozen times and finally, fourteen months after my original visit, I was issued a refund check--for $142 less than they said.  The check didn't have any explanation of why I was being given only 2/3 of my promised refund.  It turned out the insurance only paid less than half of what Western Dental thought they would.

I asked for an itemized statement of this.  They said it'd be 30-40 business days to get a statement.  I pushed harder, and after escalating two levels and spending 50 minutes on the phone, they were suddenly able to send me an email "by the end of the week."

If they'd listened to me in the first place about my not being able to come back, if they'd issued the refund promptly, if they'd at least included some kind of explanation along with the surprisingly small check, I wouldn't be leaving a mean review now.  But the whole bureaucracy around Western Dental was so deplorable I wish I could give it zero stars.  Not a good experience.  Do not recommend.< /Text>

<Rating>4< /Rating>< Text>
forget Boiling Crab( BC)... Claws is by far the best crawfish place in Orange County!

1.  The staff are so nice and friendly.
2.  The food is so yummy, probably better than BC.  The shrimp basket is so fluffy and yummy not dry like BC.
3.  The crawfish seasoning is just as good as BC, and wait it comes with sausages and corn, and potatoes, and you don't have to pay for it..Another plus is they don't charge you .50 cents for water like BC.
4.  plus they have other things you can try there that is so so so good

*** quite honestly, I don't want to tell people about how good this place is because I don't want it to turn into another BC, but I want to let the world know what a hidden gem this place is, that's why I'm writing this review</Text>

<pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNLaCcNcpKW8z1-RM2VbUUlupqF5J12IpK6fLB7=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM41T9gK_KZRdAR_l_5Q5cTpWnVzp0k-ODWIV1u=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMv1AgHOt5ov76UAGOqGWhfsRiQu47rRdB7CX6b=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pics><gmapID>0x80dd2d9f847fc75f:0x87286420dce4e0a5<//gmapID><Review>Claws was one of my families favorite restaurant until last Saturday. ¬†We patronize this location at least three a month to the point most of the waiters remember us. ¬†Prior to this incident we found the staff there pleasant and professional and the food was always tasty. On this particular day we had ordered our usual which was the peeled shrimp in the bag, pound mussels, pound of king crab legs in the bag, side order of sweet potato fries and okra with water and beer. My wife finished her mussels and proceeded to open the bag of king crab legs, which she pulled the first crab leg out of the bag and noticed an unknown black substance on the food (see pictures attached). ¬†Of course we asked the hostess who was near the door if she could send our waiter and showed her our concern. ¬†I watched her go to the back near the bar area and speak to another waiter for at least 2-3 prior to her returning. ¬†The hostess advised us that she was informed that it was normal, which my wife replied that she has never seen this before and requested that we speak with someone. ¬†The hostess left and the "Lead Waitress" (never seen nor met her in the past) came to the table and we showed her the crab and told her our concern and request that this bag be replaced. ¬†The Lead-Waitress then stoically replied that she can take the bag but will not replace it. I thought perhaps that she did not understand what exactly we were talking about so she just kept repeating her response until I realized that she knew exactly what we were saying. ¬†We then requested to see the manager which she left and went to the back for about 5 minutes. ¬†When she returned she said that the manager was indisposed. Now, I am thinking, who ever the manager is left this poor girl out to fend with the problem we have presented. I kindly told her, have your manager step out here please. ¬†My wife starts walking to the back to speak with someone who maybe familiar with us and while she does so, the Lead-waitress gets on her ear-mic and says "an unauthorized person is about to walk in the kitchen", which I reply directly "No, she is not going to go in the kitchen" (wife stops and speaks with someone at the door). ¬†While my wife is speaking in the back the conversation between myself and the Lead-Waitress starts becoming bizarre. ¬†She then tells me that they have a right to refuse to serve us. ¬†I asked, for what...because we asked for the manager. ¬†She then says, we need you to leave (now I am thinking, she wants us to get up and go out the door and say we did not pay for our food). I told her no, that will not be happening. ¬†She then says she will have to call security, which I agreed and told her the more witnesses the better. ¬†In the meantime, my wife comes back and says that they told her that there was not manager there (so now we know the Lead-Waitress just lied to us). I call the emergency line and explained that it was not an emergency but we had a small dilemma at Crows Restaurant which dispatch sent one of their Sheriffs. ¬†While waiting for the Sheriff the security guy comes in and we explain our concerns. ¬† He is looking at the crab trying to figure out what is the black substance on it, then request to take pictures of it, which we agreed. ¬†While he takes pictures, the sheriff comes in and we again explain to him what just transpired. ¬†After he sees the crab he tells us that he will talk with the young lady (Lead Waitress) and see if they will do the right thing. After the sheriff speaks with her he advises us that she says that it is the restaurants policy not to replace food for any reason but that we did not have to pay for anything if we left. ¬†Which we did. ¬†We ¬†usually recommend this restaurant to our friends and family but with what we saw on our food, and the way that it was handled by the Lead-Waitress, we will not be returning and recommend that anyone else take precautions by examine your food carefully (under the sauce) prior to eating.< /Review>< Name>

<resp>None<//resp><time>1517716261643</time><Pics>None</Pics><Gmap_id>0x80dd2d9f847fc75f:0x87286420dce4e0a5</Gmap_id>< user>

<Gmap_id>0x80dd2d9f847fc75f:0x87286420dce4e0a5< /Gmap_id><Response>None</Response><Name>Liezl Calitis</Name><review>First time I have been to this restaurant. I've been to similar restaurants with the same concept such as the Boiling Crab, Hot n' Juicy, and Captain's Boil. We were a table of six and went around 530 pm. We were seated quickly and had our bibs tied and drinks served. We basically ordered a variety bag of seafood that consisted of unpeeled shrimp, green mussels, and clams. We added in corn and sausage. We also ordered the king crab legs which were pretty meaty. We had fried calamari, coconut sea snails, sweet potato fries, cajun chicken rolls (these were tasty) and we also had the breaded tilapia (which my aunt said was a bit on the salty side). Ate with people that weren't a fan of the spicy nature, so we opted for the garlic butter sauce.  For myself, I ordered a side of the cannon ball sauce (which is a mix of all their sauces - cajun, lemon pepper, and garlic butter). I highly recommend this sauce and you can adjust the amount of spiciness to your liking. All of our food came out quickly, the servers were friendly and attentive. Overall, it's a good place to go to. Harder to get a seat if you have a large party, so if possible, go in groups of 6, or go earlier for a bigger group. They don't take reservations (this could have changed) but, it's easier to get seated with smaller groups.  I would go back!</review><Date>1507234618219<//Date>< userid>
106309178499789294155<//userid>

<GmapID>0x80dd2d9f847fc75f:0x87286420dce4e0a5< /GmapID><Pics>None</Pics>< review>
Located in a great plaza that has plenty of places to come and eat at . During peak dining hours parking is a hit or miss . So if you prefer not to look for parking , then come during non peak dining hours .
Came to this restaurant and had ordered a few things . Clam chowder and baguette to start off, surprised that the chowder was great tasting. Wish the potatoes was cut a bit smaller , but that's only my suggestion. Ordered some Cajun wings and loaded garlic carne Asada fries , the fries is amazing and now I can't just eat any carne Asada fries .
Their version of the fries ,has made it my new go to spot . I can no longer order other carne Asada fries now , the shrimp and sausage was good as well .
Overall great variety of food and will be sure to come back . Love how they also have sinks outside the restroom , for those needing to just wash their hands .< /review>

<text>My favorite crawfish boil place. I first went to the original location in Garden Grove, then their larger location in the same strip mall, and now this one in Cerritos. Their meal deals are perfect for groups of 3+ and are genuinely good deals. My usual order: peel-and-eat shrimp in Cannonball medium with sausage. Side of garlic fries, calamari, and/or fried okra. Side of rice. Sauce is garlicy, lemony, spicy goodness. I recently learned their GG location burned down, which is what may have delayed this spot from opening. I'm happy they're open now and hope everything works out because I'll continue coming here!<//text>< pics>

<username>Jenae Lien<//username><time>1538159765883<//time>< Text>
Spacious interiors - large tall foyer makes for a grand feeling as you enter. To purchase tickets, head towards the tablets propped up on tables. Easy to print tickets, no hassles.

There‚Äôs a nice dining selection with lots of great local beers and wines. Craft brews and all the candy you could want during a movie. Bar area is modern and a great place to wait for friends or catch up with friends.

Seats are nice, it costs about $16 to watch a movie here. Reserved seating, which is nice.

Park in the lot on top of Trader Joe‚Äôs and walk over, or park next to the Bank of America, no specific theatre parking here.< /Text>

< text>
It's a pretty nice theater.  They are trying the upscale thing with beer and wine and somewhat fancier food but you can tell it's a rework of a more traditional theater.  The chairs are very normal (but comfy enough) however they don't match the $17.50 ticket price.

I personally was very unhappy that the place lacks any kind of nachos or movie cheese.  Is that kind of petty?  Yes, but for me it's a staple of the experience if they're going to offer pretzels and all that.  They try and get away with having a jalapeno stuffed pretzel but don't be fooled.

Anyway, the projectors are nice, it's not packed, and you can pick your seats.  All in all, not bad, but if they added the cheese id prob pop off on a five star.  The price thing is just Culver being Culver and the seat arm rests go up so it's cool.<//text>

after having lived in Texas most of my life it was nice to go to a large auditorium like those that are found in California when one goes to the movies. I was shocked that I went to a matinee to see Matt Damon in the movie The Martian and the ticket was more than $15. Concession prices at any movie theater are always very high but these were triple what I encountered in Texas and that is just ridiculous. I understand the cost of living in California is much higherthen most places but this was almost too much to imagine for a family of four or five wanting to go to the movie and get something to eat and drink before hand. < text>
This is my favorite theater. A movie guide introduces the movie and reminds guests to turn off phones and keep noise down. This is so much more effective than the on screen reminders. He or she also stays for about 10 mins in the theater. They say no late seating, but I think that's after the 10 minutes. There is regular Cafe food and cocktails are available. <Text>Friendly staff, comfortable seating.<//Text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMiuKPhiFpX8VADMKZ46wf5hQB11RBtxZYNYrjD=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pics><response>None</response><gmapID>0x80c2ba29df23ccb3:0xdbe3df403ec205de<//gmapID></record></dataset><record>

< review>
New updated review for ArcLight:

Since ArcLight took over this location, they have really turned it around. The interior is much nicer and modern. Their bar seems like it can fit a good amount of people. The actual theater rooms have been upgraded with new seats. There's actually air conditioning this time! They have machines in which you can either buy or print out tickets, making the process much faster. Culver City now has it's own theater worthy of it's movie-loving residents.

---------------------------------
Older review:

This is an older theater that probably hasn't been renovated in a long time. I saw Thor 2 here so the theater was packed and that's when I learned they either don't have AC or it wasn't working that day which made for a really stuffy theater room filled with the stench of old snacks and body odor. I almost wanted to step out because of how uncomfortably stuffy it was.

I came back to watch Big Hero 6 at the final stretch of it's movie run so there was only 1 other group in the theater room and it was much more bearable.

Parking options include on the street, the parking garage at Trader Joe's which is 2 hours free or the garage in downtown Culver which is also free for 2 hours.

I wouldn't recommend this theater for a new movie showing.< /review>

< Review>
As with all ArcLight Cinemas there is a full bar (yes you can take your drink into the movie), early seat selection, and larger snack options.

There are large public parking lots around downtown Culver so parking is never really an issue. Remember that they will check your bag, not too thoroughly, but they do check.</Review>

< Review>
The art deco building is that typical cinema architecture. Not my personal cup of tea but at least it doesn't clash with the nearby historical Culver City hotel. The interior offers a bar and a menu of eats to cater for the those that want to mix dinner and a movie. There's a set of touch computer screens if you prefer to pick up tickets at the cinema. The movie experience is good and I've never had a problem with noisy or disrespectful patrons. So this is a good place to catch a flic and grab a bite to eat.</Review>

<Date>1489615995960</Date><rating>5<//rating>< Text>
I can never say anything bad about Arclight. It's my favorite movie theater chain by a landslide. The Culver location is one of their smaller and quieter locations. They have free parking (granted it is a little bit of a walk) and an excellent location. It is the spot my wife and I go to when we don't want to deal with the crowds at Hollywood. The only time I wouldn't come here is if I wanted to see a movie on a HUGE screen and/or IMAX. Over than that, flawless.< /Text>

Arclight cinemas is a premium cinema/theater company. Their seats are awesome and super comfy; their sound and picture quality is pretty dope. At the beginning of every film, they have an introduction by one of their staff checking "arclight standards" for their films. The costs of tickets these days are fairly pricey, yet reasonable for the perquisites, as mentioned.< /review>

<time>1518949897841< /time><Rating>2< /Rating>< Text>
The theater has a policy that doesn't allow outside food into their cinemas...no problem with their policy, I just wish I knew about it before arriving at ticket validation. The attendant told me to through away the remaining half of a sandwich, take it to my car, or sit outside and eat it. These were their best option even though I also had $40 in items purchased from their concession stand. I sat outside and ate the sandwich BUT THEN about an hour in the movie, THE WHOLE THEATER LOST ELECTRICITY. The entire building had to be evacuated. Shall I say, "self evacuated" because there were no announcements, assisting attendants, or emergency response teams. I guess ArcLight cares more about training staff on how to reject patrons who bring in outside leftovers than addressing real operational issues. This was a horrible movie-going experience and I didnt even get a chance to see the end of the film.< /Text>
